{"key":"processedPost-8906181","value":{"id":8906181,"first":8904724,"last":8913236,"when":1221062577,"utime":"09/10/08 07:02 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />plus, you're way too technical.&nbsp; they dont even really need any light at all<br /></blockquote><br /><br />That's flat-out wrong. He isn't growing button mushrooms for the grocery store. While dim room light might be enough for a few <i>P cubensis</i> pins to develop, bright high frequency light such as is recommended, and the original poster is using, is perfect to develop a stellar, stunning pinset and flush.&nbsp; The mycelium requires bright light to form abundant primordia, and the developing fruits need a regular light schedule all the way to harvest for best results.<br /><br />It's normal as you've experienced for the mycelium to partially envelop the vermiculite.&nbsp; Keep it well misted, and provide plenty of air exchange.&nbsp; I'm no fan of the pmp either.&nbsp; Some (sub)strains will do OK in them, but most require much more fresh air than an air pump can supply.&nbsp; It's more than just getting rid of the CO2-It's about <i>fresh air</i>, which fruiting mushrooms love.&nbsp; I'd fan the terrarium out whenever you can.<br />RR","title":"Re: are these cakes colonizing in the FC??","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}